english:
  title: A Poor Village Song
  author: Sung Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Dark clouds fill the sky, the north wind rages with fury,
    Woodpeckers tap and peck at trees along the stream.
    Beneath the mountain stands a cottage small as a snail's shell,
    Three sons and two elders dwelling together in one home.

    One son takes his axe and goes to gather wood,
    One son follows rabbit tracks across the distant hills,
    The youngest cries and begs for rice to fill his belly,
    While grandmother sits mending socks, grandfather twists rope.

    The stone-heated floor holds its meager warmth,
    The earthen pot bubbles with bean porridge,
    The ox lows and chews the chaff of beans,
    The rooster perches in the rafters.

    All creatures, all people, struggle in this lean year,
    Their lives worn thin by hunger's grind.
    The child tugs at grandfather's sleeve, touches his brow,
    Together they step outside to gaze at mountains blanketed in snow.
  footnotes:
    - This poem, written by the Joseon scholar-official Sung Hyeon (1439-1504), portrays the quiet dignity of rural poverty with remarkable tenderness and realism for its era.
